Okay.

115
00:04:17,019 --> 00:04:18,713
Whoa.

116
00:04:19,019 --> 00:04:21,208
It's like a spa,
but on the moon.

117
00:04:21,289 --> 00:04:25,102
Just, uh, put on some
smooth jazz and some slippers,

118
00:04:25,179 --> 00:04:26,622
light some candles,
and, uh...

119
00:04:26,699 --> 00:04:28,221
And you'd
blow yourself up.

120
00:04:28,298 --> 00:04:29,919
See, when these doors
are closed,

121
00:04:29,996 --> 00:04:33,093
it pressurizes the room
up to three atmospheres.

122
00:04:33,170 --> 00:04:36,902
It will radically decrease
healing time.

123
00:04:36,979 --> 00:04:39,230
This is a world-class
hyperbaric chamber.

124
00:04:39,307 --> 00:04:40,732
Yeah, no, I know.

125
00:04:40,809 --> 00:04:42,703
But moon spa
sounds better.

126
00:04:43,353 --> 00:04:44,448
Oh, hey, uh,

127
00:04:44,525 --> 00:04:46,442
I've got some requisitions
that need approval.

128
00:04:46,519 --> 00:04:47,734
Does that go
through you, or...

129
00:04:47,811 --> 00:04:49,070
You choose
an interim chief yet?

130
00:04:49,147 --> 00:04:50,211
Almost.

131
00:04:50,288 --> 00:04:53,772
Just going over
a few final considerations.

132
00:04:53,849 --> 00:04:55,473
Yeah,
it's a tough decision.

133
00:04:55,550 --> 00:04:58,552
I mean, you want somebody good,
but not better than you, right?

134
00:04:58,629 --> 00:05:01,684
Like a solid substitute player,
maybe plays half the game.

135
00:05:01,761 --> 00:05:02,926
I'm sorry?

136
00:05:03,116 --> 00:05:05,386
You want a third-,
maybe fourth-round draft pack

137
00:05:05,463 --> 00:05:07,579
so your people really miss you
when you're gone.

138
00:05:07,656 --> 00:05:08,677
I mean, we all know
what happens

139
00:05:08,754 --> 00:05:09,937
when LeBron's on the bench,
right?

140
00:05:10,014 --> 00:05:13,075
The crowd goes wild...
"MVP, MVP, MV..."

141
00:05:13,576 --> 00:05:15,530
You're LeBron.
They want you back on the court

142
00:05:15,607 --> 00:05:17,200
as soon as possible.

143
00:05:17,385 --> 00:05:18,931
Not into basketball?

144
00:05:19,008 --> 00:05:22,099
Okay, uh,
enjoy your moon spa.

145
00:05:27,004 --> 00:05:29,401
Hey.
You paged me to the breezeway.

146
00:05:29,478 --> 00:05:31,784
I wanted to see you, and...
Whoa.

147
00:05:34,315 --> 00:05:35,524
How was this morning?

148
00:05:35,601 --> 00:05:38,315
Uh, Leo slept in,
and Betty made breakfast.

149
00:05:38,392 --> 00:05:40,421
It was fine.
She was asking for you.

150
00:05:40,498 --> 00:05:42,094
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

151
00:05:45,479 --> 00:05:47,071
We need help, please!

152
00:05:47,148 --> 00:05:49,110
- Are you hurt?
- They are! They're in the back!

153
00:05:49,187 --> 00:05:51,519
Who?
Our stupid parents.

154
00:05:53,151 --> 00:05:54,647
He was bleeding a lot.

155
00:05:54,724 --> 00:05:56,520
I used the whole roll
of paper towels.

156
00:05:56,597 --> 00:05:58,053
Uh, we need a gurney, now!

157
00:05:58,130 --> 00:06:00,170
Two. My mom was also
on the motorcycle.

158
00:06:00,247 --> 00:06:02,083
Honey, did you put the van's
emergency brake on?

159
00:06:02,160 --> 00:06:03,645
Yes, I'm not an idiot
like you and Dad

160
00:06:03,722 --> 00:06:05,034
who just crashed
a death machine!

161
00:06:05,111 --> 00:06:07,013
We were trying to avoid
hitting the dog!

162
00:06:07,090 --> 00:06:09,021
And please don't yell at me.
I'm your mother.

163
00:06:09,098 --> 00:06:10,115
You're not acting
like it!

164
00:06:10,192 --> 00:06:12,534
- He wasn't wearing a helmet?
- Weonly had one. He made me wear it.

165
00:06:12,611 --> 00:06:14,213
We were just going
around the block!

166
00:06:14,290 --> 00:06:15,894
Where's that gurney?

167
00:06:17,490 --> 00:06:23,031
<i>♪ There's a somebody
I'm wanting to see ♪</i>

168
00:06:23,456 --> 00:06:28,219
<i>♪ I hope that he
turns out to be ♪</i>

169
00:06:28,784 --> 00:06:35,849
<i>♪ Someone who'll watch
over me ♪</i>

170
00:06:35,926 --> 00:06:37,019
That's nice.

171
00:06:37,096 --> 00:06:39,742
Cece, you really need to be
back in bed.

172
00:06:42,938 --> 00:06:45,022
<i>♪ I'm a little lamb
who's lost... ♪</i>

173
00:06:45,099 --> 00:06:47,736
Uh, exactly. I mean, she went
into V-Tach at least four times

174
00:06:47,813 --> 00:06:49,039
in the middle of the night.

175
00:06:49,116 --> 00:06:51,780
And until the dialysis
restores her electrolytes,

176
00:06:51,857 --> 00:06:53,675
she's at risk
for arrhythmias.

177
00:06:53,752 --> 00:06:55,661
We could start her
on an amiodarone drip.

178
00:06:55,738 --> 00:06:57,338
All right, well let's keep that
as a plan

179
00:06:57,415 --> 00:06:59,476
and just keep rechecking
her potassium.

180
00:06:59,553 --> 00:07:00,549
And how's Nisha?

181
00:07:00,626 --> 00:07:02,610
She's septic,
white count of 22,000,

182
00:07:02,687 --> 00:07:04,381
and we started her
on pressors.

183
00:07:04,458 --> 00:07:06,360
Her parents are on a flight back
from Tokyo now,

184
00:07:06,437 --> 00:07:10,516
but until they get here,
Cece won't leave her side.

185
00:07:10,676 --> 00:07:13,030
So, let's make sure that she
wears a mask and gloves.

186
00:07:13,107 --> 00:07:17,141
Yeah. Send for an ABG
and, uh, lactic acid.

187
00:07:17,739 --> 00:07:19,054
Thanks for keeping
an eye on her.

188
00:07:19,131 --> 00:07:20,318
She's a very sweet woman,

189
00:07:20,395 --> 00:07:21,780
but she's so aggressive
with the...

190
00:07:21,857 --> 00:07:22,855
- The matchmaking?
- Yes.

191
00:07:22,932 --> 00:07:23,941
- Right?
- Yeah, no kidding.

192
00:07:24,018 --> 00:07:25,775
She asked me about my status,
my relationship history,

193
00:07:25,852 --> 00:07:26,912
my 10-year plan.

194
00:07:26,989 --> 00:07:28,836
Career-
and relationship-wise.

195
00:07:28,997 --> 00:07:30,535
That's why I can't go back
in there.

196
00:07:30,612 --> 00:07:31,940
At least you can tell her
to back off

197
00:07:32,017 --> 00:07:33,057
because you have Maggie.

198
00:07:33,134 --> 00:07:35,096
Yeah, but you should just tell
her you have work, you know?

199
00:07:35,173 --> 00:07:36,272
And what does that mean?

200
00:07:36,349 --> 00:07:37,883
Like, that you're married
to your work.

201
00:07:37,960 --> 00:07:38,965
I mean...

202
00:07:39,051 --> 00:07:40,060
But I'm not.

203
00:07:40,137 --> 00:07:43,094
Oh, come on. We all are.
Just you are especially.

204
00:07:43,227 --> 00:07:44,872
Excuse me?

205
00:07:45,419 --> 00:07:47,951
Have you seen the, uh,
hyperbaric chamber?

206
00:07:48,028 --> 00:07:49,578
That thing is finished,
so it's probably worth

207
00:07:49,655 --> 00:07:51,351
taking a little peek.

208
00:07:53,808 --> 00:07:54,961
You're very successful.

209
00:07:55,038 --> 00:07:56,455
Oh, very.
Very successful.

210
00:07:56,532 --> 00:07:58,304
Yeah, but I'm not married...

211
00:07:58,456 --> 00:08:00,000
That's cool.

212
00:08:00,147 --> 00:08:01,539
Me neither.

213
00:08:08,747 --> 00:08:09,816
Oh, hi.

214
00:08:09,893 --> 00:08:11,560
Um, may I remind you

215
00:08:11,637 --> 00:08:15,292
that many people still
call me "Chief" out of habit?

216
00:08:15,369 --> 00:08:17,978
I mean, I can ensure
a seamless transition...

217
00:08:18,055 --> 00:08:19,810
It's not going to
be you.

218
00:08:19,887 --> 00:08:21,211
Wait, why on Earth not?

219
00:08:21,288 --> 00:08:22,856
Because...

220
00:08:23,098 --> 00:08:24,796
One day,
I want the job back,

221
00:08:24,873 --> 00:08:27,313
and... you're
a first-round draft pack,

222
00:08:27,390 --> 00:08:29,432
and no one removes
a game starter from the court...

223
00:08:29,509 --> 00:08:31,312
I mean office.

224
00:08:32,030 --> 00:08:34,367
Since when
do you like sports?

225
00:08:38,278 --> 00:08:40,578
- Where are you going?
- To the moon spa.

226
00:08:41,207 --> 00:08:42,655
Where it's quiet.

227
00:08:46,510 --> 00:08:48,164
Her creatinine
keeps climbing,

228
00:08:48,241 --> 00:08:51,649
so let's order an ultrasound
with contrast and a cardiac MRI.

229
00:08:51,726 --> 00:08:53,318
I just want to make sure
her tanking kidneys

230
00:08:53,395 --> 00:08:55,662
aren't tanking her heart.

231
00:08:56,830 --> 00:08:57,915
I, uh...

232
00:08:57,992 --> 00:09:00,096
I understand why you don't want
to go in there.

233
00:09:00,189 --> 00:09:02,624
I mean, I'm married
to general surgery, too.

234
00:09:02,701 --> 00:09:04,464
I get it.
I relate.

235
00:09:04,541 --> 00:09:05,782
Helm, no.

236
00:09:05,859 --> 00:09:08,531
I... It's... Just...
Go get the MRI, please.

237
00:09:08,608 --> 00:09:10,154
Oh, Meredith!
There she is.

238
00:09:10,231 --> 00:09:11,227
Can we talk?

239
00:09:11,304 --> 00:09:12,333
What happened
to the honeymoon?

240
00:09:12,410 --> 00:09:13,398
What happened
to your face?

241
00:09:13,475 --> 00:09:14,521
I forgot sunscreen.

242
00:09:14,598 --> 00:09:16,223
And I want to
save the world.

243
00:09:16,300 --> 00:09:18,029
Oh.
Come on.

244
00:09:21,759 --> 00:09:23,444
What do you think?

245
00:09:25,824 --> 00:09:27,759
I think...

246
00:09:27,946 --> 00:09:29,324
Alex married up.

247
00:09:29,401 --> 00:09:31,502
Right? If she does this,
I can retire

248
00:09:31,579 --> 00:09:33,081
and buy a bigger boat
than Avery.

249
00:09:33,158 --> 00:09:35,036
And also save lives.

250
00:09:35,113 --> 00:09:37,044
And this would work
for all types of cancers?

251
00:09:37,121 --> 00:09:39,826
Leukemias, adenocarcinomas,
liver hepatomas?

252
00:09:39,903 --> 00:09:40,992
Maybe? I don't know!

253
00:09:41,069 --> 00:09:43,076
But if we can isolate
the cancer cells

254
00:09:43,153 --> 00:09:44,456
and locate the gene sequence

255
00:09:44,533 --> 00:09:46,124
that makes them grow
uncontrollably,

256
00:09:46,201 --> 00:09:48,036
then, theoretically,

257
00:09:48,113 --> 00:09:50,916
we can make the anti-DNA
sequence that'll stop it.

258
00:09:50,993 --> 00:09:52,464
Well, then you could use it
for anything

259
00:09:52,541 --> 00:09:53,794
that goes wrong in the body.

260
00:09:53,871 --> 00:09:55,487
- Exactly.
- Well, now I'm pissed

261
00:09:55,564 --> 00:09:57,460
because you came back early
from your honeymoon

262
00:09:57,537 --> 00:09:59,334
to wave the future of medicine
in my face

263
00:09:59,411 --> 00:10:00,890
and take it to Boston?

264
00:10:01,028 --> 00:10:04,245
I came back to ask you to create
a fellowship for me.

265
00:10:04,322 --> 00:10:06,726
So that I can keep working
on mini livers and this.

266
00:10:06,803 --> 00:10:08,336
Mostly this.

267
00:10:08,629 --> 00:10:09,972
With you.

268
00:10:10,149 --> 00:10:12,531
Give me an hour to get approval
from Bailey.

269
00:10:18,323 --> 00:10:19,526
So, you were lucky.

270
00:10:19,603 --> 00:10:21,025
You may have gotten away
with a few bruises

271
00:10:21,102 --> 00:10:22,890
- and cuts on your hands.
- I'm so sorry.

272
00:10:22,967 --> 00:10:24,695
Don't apologize.
This is my job.

273
00:10:24,772 --> 00:10:26,190
No, I'm so embarrassed.

274
00:10:26,267 --> 00:10:28,815
We decided to take a ride,
just around the block.

275
00:10:28,892 --> 00:10:30,584
Doug bought the bike
a few weeks ago.

276
00:10:30,661 --> 00:10:32,018
He works in HR,
and frankly,

277
00:10:32,095 --> 00:10:34,694
I think he might be having some
sort of mild mid-life crisis.

278
00:10:34,771 --> 00:10:36,276
But he had a motorcycle
in college,

279
00:10:36,353 --> 00:10:38,140
and it made him happy,
and I want to support him,

280
00:10:38,217 --> 00:10:39,229
but I don't like it.

281
00:10:39,306 --> 00:10:41,718
But then I saw him in the garage
in a greasy T-shirt,

282
00:10:41,795 --> 00:10:45,117
and he looked good.
Like, 1993 good.

283
00:10:45,218 --> 00:10:46,792
Mom. You okay?

284
00:10:46,869 --> 00:10:48,164
Sweetie,
where's the dog?

285
00:10:48,241 --> 00:10:49,656
He got away.

286
00:10:50,174 --> 00:10:51,300
Wait, in here?

287
00:10:51,377 --> 00:10:53,084
You brought the dog
in the hospital?

288
00:10:53,161 --> 00:10:54,275
I'm so sorry.

289
00:10:54,352 --> 00:10:55,331
Again.

290
00:10:55,408 --> 00:10:57,875
Uh, I'll check
on your husband, okay?

291
00:10:58,656 --> 00:11:01,495
- Qadri, go find the dog.
- Uh...

292
00:11:01,572 --> 00:11:03,023
Qadri.
I was third in my class.

293
00:11:03,100 --> 00:11:04,104
Hey.

294
00:11:04,181 --> 00:11:05,465
Dad has a nasty scalp lac,

295
00:11:05,542 --> 00:11:07,374
and I felt a step-off
on the right temporal area,

296
00:11:07,451 --> 00:11:09,398
so we've got to rule out
a skull fracture.

297
00:11:11,337 --> 00:11:14,492
I thought military people
prided themselves on their punctuality.

298
00:11:14,569 --> 00:11:15,753
I paged you
20 minutes ago.

299
00:11:15,830 --> 00:11:17,752
I was in the E.R.
and you paged me to a stairwell

300
00:11:17,829 --> 00:11:19,291
- and then you weren't there.
- Well,

301
00:11:19,368 --> 00:11:21,492
I had to walk.
I was stressed.

302
00:11:21,906 --> 00:11:23,750
And attendings
are never wrong.

303
00:11:25,285 --> 00:11:26,665
You're stressing
about the thing we both know

304
00:11:26,742 --> 00:11:28,395
and can't talk about,
right?

305
00:11:28,472 --> 00:11:30,964
I know. I'm working with
Dr. Shepherd and Major Hunt today,

306
00:11:31,041 --> 00:11:33,203
and I feel like I'm lying
to my commanding officer.

307
00:11:33,330 --> 00:11:35,878
I hate secrets.
I've always hated keeping them.

308
00:11:35,955 --> 00:11:38,633
They start out as these tiny
seeds of information,

309
00:11:38,710 --> 00:11:42,711
and then they grow into these
terrifying Venus flytraps

310
00:11:42,788 --> 00:11:45,916
that will eat your relationships
alive, one by one.

311
00:11:45,993 --> 00:11:47,204
We have to do something.

312
00:11:47,281 --> 00:11:48,892
We?
Yes.

313
00:11:49,164 --> 00:11:50,226
Amelia's happy.

314
00:11:50,303 --> 00:11:52,683
She's like "Leave It To Beaver,"
co-parenting happy.

315
00:11:52,760 --> 00:11:56,868
She and Owen are completely
oblivious about the love child

316
00:11:56,945 --> 00:12:00,067
that is just going to drop
on them like a bomb!

317
00:12:00,504 --> 00:12:02,654
Babies are not bombs.
I'm very sorry.

318
00:12:02,731 --> 00:12:04,101
I don't know what's wrong
with me.

319
00:12:04,178 --> 00:12:05,426
I used to have it together.

320
00:12:05,503 --> 00:12:07,317
I used to be sane,
but then HIPAA

321
00:12:07,394 --> 00:12:10,176
and half-marriage proposals
and not enough sleep.

322
00:12:10,253 --> 00:12:11,563
Dr. Avery proposed?

323
00:12:11,640 --> 00:12:12,838
Go away.
We're not friends.

324
00:12:12,915 --> 00:12:14,724
- Well, you paged me.
- Go. Go!

325
00:12:15,869 --> 00:12:16,947
Hey.
Hey.

326
00:12:17,033 --> 00:12:18,078
- You okay?
- Yes.

327
00:12:18,155 --> 00:12:20,374
I'm really sorry I didn't come
back with the milk last night.

328
00:12:20,451 --> 00:12:22,317
I... I drove to the store,
and then I...

329
00:12:22,394 --> 00:12:26,300
I drove to the wrong house,
and I got tired, so I just...

330
00:12:26,377 --> 00:12:28,184
I stayed there.
But I did buy the milk.

331
00:12:28,261 --> 00:12:29,603
Dr. Avery?

332
00:12:29,858 --> 00:12:31,435
Nisha's cultures are back.

333
00:12:31,919 --> 00:12:33,103
Uh...

334
00:12:33,236 --> 00:12:34,318
Uh, can I...
Can we talk later?

335
00:12:34,395 --> 00:12:35,557
Mm-hmm.

336
00:12:38,955 --> 00:12:42,193
We need to isolate her
and get her into O.R., stat.

337
00:12:42,439 --> 00:12:44,164
Cece, I need you on the other
side of that glass

338
00:12:44,241 --> 00:12:46,101
- right now, please.
- Her parents aren't here yet

339
00:12:46,178 --> 00:12:48,871
- I don't want to leave her alone.
- Right now. Please. Thank you.

340
00:12:48,985 --> 00:12:51,116
Nisha, you've got
an infection, okay?

341
00:12:51,193 --> 00:12:52,479
It's called
necrotizing fasciitis.

342
00:12:52,556 --> 00:12:53,833
It's very serious.
We're gonna get you

343
00:12:53,910 --> 00:12:55,738
straight
into the O.R., okay?

344
00:12:55,815 --> 00:12:58,568
Tell my mom I love her.

345
00:12:58,645 --> 00:13:00,488
Tell her thank you.

346
00:13:00,565 --> 00:13:01,609
Tell her...

347
00:13:01,686 --> 00:13:03,333
You're just
getting started, Nisha.

348
00:13:03,410 --> 00:13:04,682
Do you hear me?

349
00:13:04,759 --> 00:13:07,060
You are just
getting started.

350
00:13:07,609 --> 00:13:09,843
Schmitt, wait.
We're not taking her to the O.R.

351
00:13:09,920 --> 00:13:11,255
Let me get her
to the basement.

352
00:13:11,332 --> 00:13:13,505
- What's in the basement?
- I got to find Bailey.

353
00:13:17,855 --> 00:13:19,964
You better be here
to wonder and marvel

354
00:13:20,041 --> 00:13:21,424
at the future
of medicine.

355
00:13:21,501 --> 00:13:24,255
That's exactly
what I'm doing.

356
00:13:24,970 --> 00:13:28,290
Jo Wilson came up with
an insanely brilliant idea

357
00:13:28,367 --> 00:13:30,551
that will change the way
we do our jobs.

358
00:13:30,689 --> 00:13:32,952
And I would like
to offer her

359
00:13:33,029 --> 00:13:35,409
a surgical innovation
fellowship.

360
00:13:35,493 --> 00:13:37,333
That is a thing
that doesn't exist.

361
00:13:37,410 --> 00:13:39,466
Exactly. That's why
we should invent it...

362
00:13:39,543 --> 00:13:41,466
So we can wonder
and marvel some more.

363
00:13:41,543 --> 00:13:45,116
I just spent a lot
of money to make money, Grey.

364
00:13:45,193 --> 00:13:48,018
I need to let it make some money
before I spend any more.

365
00:13:48,095 --> 00:13:49,303
We'd get to keep Alex.

366
00:13:49,380 --> 00:13:52,595
The only way I could afford
a new fellowship for Jo Wilson

367
00:13:52,672 --> 00:13:56,517
is with the salary I'd free up
by losing Alex Karev.

368
00:13:56,594 --> 00:14:00,400
But I have to replace Karev,
so there is no money.

369
00:14:00,953 --> 00:14:02,645
My patient has
necrotizing fasciitis.

370
00:14:02,722 --> 00:14:03,882
I need
the hyperbaric chamber.

371
00:14:03,959 --> 00:14:04,876
I think
it's her only shot.

372
00:14:04,953 --> 00:14:05,985
You want to debride her
in here?

373
00:14:06,062 --> 00:14:06,911
How would you
do that?

374
00:14:06,988 --> 00:14:08,429
You can't use
any electricity in here.

375
00:14:08,506 --> 00:14:09,962
- No cautery, no...
- It's okay, I'll go old school.

376
00:14:10,039 --> 00:14:11,751
I'll just use a scalpel.
No, you sit in here.

377
00:14:11,828 --> 00:14:13,265
You don't operate in here.

378
00:14:13,342 --> 00:14:14,496
Think of it like a spa.

379
00:14:14,573 --> 00:14:16,220
Debriding in high-flow oxygen
has shown

380
00:14:16,297 --> 00:14:18,315
to improve survival outcomes
in crush injuries

381
00:14:18,392 --> 00:14:19,259
with wound infections.

382
00:14:19,336 --> 00:14:21,514
Debriding with a scalpel
would take hours.

383
00:14:21,591 --> 00:14:24,822
You'd be putting your staff
at risk for decompression illness,

384
00:14:24,899 --> 00:14:26,216
a-and you'd be stuck
in here.

385
00:14:26,293 --> 00:14:28,294
You couldn't leave until
it was depressurized.

386
00:14:28,371 --> 00:14:29,791
Okay, this thing
is useless.

387
00:14:29,868 --> 00:14:31,462
I say we sell it
and keep Jo Wilson.

388
00:14:31,539 --> 00:14:33,314
Grey, the answer is no.
Avery...

389
00:14:33,391 --> 00:14:35,441
If DeLuca hadn't pulled me out
of the way of that van,

390
00:14:35,518 --> 00:14:36,938
then that woman
might be fine.

391
00:14:37,015 --> 00:14:38,790
All right? She might have
been the one that called 911

392
00:14:38,867 --> 00:14:40,456
and put me in the ambulance
for all that I know,

393
00:14:40,533 --> 00:14:41,794
and I'm here, I'm okay.

394
00:14:41,871 --> 00:14:43,446
I'm standing
in a medical spaceship

395
00:14:43,523 --> 00:14:45,112
that you built
for us to save lives,

396
00:14:45,189 --> 00:14:47,790
and the only one standing in the
way of me saving hers is you.

397
00:14:48,547 --> 00:14:49,834
Please.

398
00:14:55,014 --> 00:14:56,020
So?

399
00:14:56,097 --> 00:14:57,907
She built a submarine
in the basement,

400
00:14:57,984 --> 00:14:59,493
and apparently
there's no money now.

401
00:14:59,570 --> 00:15:00,686
So, what do we do now?

402
00:15:00,763 --> 00:15:03,135
I don't know. Wait for
more funds to become available?

403
00:15:03,212 --> 00:15:04,872
I'd say for now,
just go to Boston.

404
00:15:04,949 --> 00:15:05,985
As much as I hate it.

405
00:15:06,062 --> 00:15:07,057
We can't.

406
00:15:07,134 --> 00:15:08,075
It's only a year.

407
00:15:08,152 --> 00:15:10,055
We go, you learn
more cool stuff, we come home.

408
00:15:10,132 --> 00:15:12,915
We can't because I already
called them and told them no.

409
00:15:13,479 --> 00:15:14,985
I don't have a job.

410
00:15:15,062 --> 00:15:16,563
Anywhere.

411
00:15:20,897 --> 00:15:23,645
All right, once this
door closes, you're in.

412
00:15:23,722 --> 00:15:27,438
If we depressurize too quick,
you will get nitrogen toxicity.

413
00:15:27,515 --> 00:15:30,025
You're also looking
at eardrum rupture,

414
00:15:30,102 --> 00:15:34,645
lung collapse, sinus damage,
changes in vision, uh...

415
00:15:34,722 --> 00:15:36,783
Don't forget to pop your ears!

416
00:15:49,942 --> 00:15:52,283
Megan Salinas
to Oncology.

417
00:15:52,889 --> 00:15:54,512
Doug's CT shows
a skull fracture

418
00:15:54,589 --> 00:15:55,864
with a small bleed
underneath it.

419
00:15:55,941 --> 00:15:57,433
I gonna need to take him
to the O.R.

420
00:15:57,510 --> 00:15:59,542
and drain it
and relieve the pressure.

421
00:15:59,619 --> 00:16:01,601
He needs brain surgery?

422
00:16:01,678 --> 00:16:03,038
Actual brain surgery?

423
00:16:03,115 --> 00:16:04,628
Honestly, it could've been
a lot worse.

424
00:16:04,705 --> 00:16:06,519
Motorcycle accidents
without helmets...

425
00:16:06,596 --> 00:16:09,073
Honey, maybe you should take
Hank to the cafeteria.

426
00:16:09,162 --> 00:16:10,480
I want to stay
with you.

427
00:16:10,557 --> 00:16:11,642
Are you crazy?!

428
00:16:11,719 --> 00:16:13,048
I'm not leaving you two
alone again.

429
00:16:13,125 --> 00:16:15,335
Wynnie, I am so sorry,
but we'll be okay.

430
00:16:15,412 --> 00:16:16,972
No, I had to drive you
to the hospital,

431
00:16:17,049 --> 00:16:18,593
and I don't even
have a license!

432
00:16:18,670 --> 00:16:19,902
She has
her learner's permit.

433
00:16:19,979 --> 00:16:21,593
No, I'm a terrible driver.

434
00:16:21,670 --> 00:16:23,556
We could have all
been dead today.

435
00:16:24,545 --> 00:16:25,631
Dad!

436
00:16:26,740 --> 00:16:28,123
Hey, guys.

437
00:16:28,334 --> 00:16:30,102
Don't worry. I'm fine.

438
00:16:30,179 --> 00:16:32,437
He's got a little bruise
on the inside of his head,

439
00:16:32,514 --> 00:16:34,027
but I'm gonna fix it
right up, okay?

440
00:16:34,104 --> 00:16:35,670
Mm-hmm.

441
00:16:37,049 --> 00:16:38,546
Well, surgery
shouldn't be too long,

442
00:16:38,623 --> 00:16:40,120
so I can show you
where you can wait, okay?

443
00:16:40,197 --> 00:16:41,333
I got him!

444
00:16:41,410 --> 00:16:44,548
He may have eaten someone's
Jell-O, but I think he's okay.

445
00:16:44,625 --> 00:16:45,608
Here's your dog.

446
00:16:45,685 --> 00:16:46,738
Oh, no,
he's not our dog.

447
00:16:46,815 --> 00:16:48,524
He's a stray we almost hit.

448
00:16:48,601 --> 00:16:49,777
Can we keep him?

449
00:16:49,854 --> 00:16:50,878
I'm allergic.

450
00:16:50,955 --> 00:16:52,709
So lame.

451
00:16:53,078 --> 00:16:55,495
No, don't just
let him go...

452
00:16:55,572 --> 00:16:56,982
Qadri.

453
00:16:59,381 --> 00:17:00,962
Third in my class!

454
00:17:01,534 --> 00:17:03,472
She's still hyperkalemic,

455
00:17:03,549 --> 00:17:06,306
even with the dialysis
and the insulin drip.

456
00:17:06,383 --> 00:17:08,858
Is she on her way
up to the MRI?

457
00:17:08,935 --> 00:17:11,983
Yes, uh, radiology should be
sending the results any minute,

458
00:17:12,060 --> 00:17:14,288
and I asked Dr. Pierce
to meet you in the tech room

459
00:17:14,365 --> 00:17:15,394
so she could have
a look.

460
00:17:15,471 --> 00:17:16,939
Great work, Helm.

461
00:17:17,060 --> 00:17:18,287
Thank you.

462
00:17:19,685 --> 00:17:21,595
Why are you looking at me
like that?

463
00:17:21,896 --> 00:17:23,462
Nothing.
I'm not.

464
00:17:23,549 --> 00:17:25,392
- Hey. You needed me?
- Yep.

465
00:17:25,469 --> 00:17:27,079
<i>Shea Drexler
to Pathology.</i>

466
00:17:27,156 --> 00:17:28,343
Shea Drexler...

467
00:17:28,420 --> 00:17:29,577
What do you got?

468
00:17:29,654 --> 00:17:31,173
Motorcycle injury.

469
00:17:31,250 --> 00:17:32,316
No helmet.

470
00:17:32,393 --> 00:17:33,457
Stupid.

471
00:17:33,543 --> 00:17:34,553
Yep.

472
00:17:34,630 --> 00:17:35,682
You?

473
00:17:35,759 --> 00:17:37,684
Matchmaker
with a bad heart.

474
00:17:37,761 --> 00:17:39,161
- Ironic.
- She's a matchmaker?

475
00:17:39,238 --> 00:17:41,851
- Those still exist?
- I guess Internet dating is just so...

476
00:17:41,928 --> 00:17:43,196
- Deceitful?
- Depressing.

477
00:17:43,273 --> 00:17:44,488
Exactly.

478
00:17:44,839 --> 00:17:46,283
Is there a dog in here?

479
00:17:46,360 --> 00:17:47,423
- What?
- What?

480
00:17:47,500 --> 00:17:49,093
No. Nothing.

481
00:17:50,394 --> 00:17:54,223
I had an 89-year-old patient
in L.A. who hired a matchmaker

482
00:17:54,300 --> 00:17:56,694
to help her find a man
who could drive at night.

483
00:17:56,890 --> 00:17:58,366
That was
her only requirement.

484
00:17:58,443 --> 00:17:59,458
That's so sweet.

485
00:17:59,535 --> 00:18:00,689
Well, they take
the work out for you.

486
00:18:00,766 --> 00:18:02,770
They weed out the creeps
and the emotional baggage.

487
00:18:02,847 --> 00:18:04,997
They get you
to that pre-vetted place.

488
00:18:05,074 --> 00:18:06,528
Like where Owen and I are.

489
00:18:06,605 --> 00:18:08,558
Which is where, exactly?

490
00:18:08,635 --> 00:18:10,342
Where he's gonna drive her
around at night?

491
00:18:10,419 --> 00:18:11,640
I think so.

492
00:18:11,717 --> 00:18:12,918
I hope so.

493
00:18:12,995 --> 00:18:14,152
I don't.

494
00:18:14,369 --> 00:18:16,405
I don't hope that for you.

495
00:18:16,482 --> 00:18:17,463
What?

496
00:18:17,540 --> 00:18:18,714
Why not?

497
00:18:18,832 --> 00:18:19,987
I just...
You know what?

498
00:18:20,064 --> 00:18:21,485
Don't answer that
until you have dealt

499
00:18:21,562 --> 00:18:22,974
with your own half-proposal.

500
00:18:23,051 --> 00:18:24,727
Jackson told me
I'm married to my work.

501
00:18:24,804 --> 00:18:25,842
Am I married to my work?

502
00:18:25,919 --> 00:18:28,382
Oh, he just throws that word
around a lot, doesn't he?

503
00:18:28,459 --> 00:18:31,054
Oh, they sent
the studies.

504
00:18:33,008 --> 00:18:34,971
I may be a little rusty
with hearts,

